%S A397444 0,5,12,29,48,77,108,149,192,245,300,365,432,509,588,677,768,869,972,
%T A397444 1085,1200,1325,1452,1589,1728,1877,2028,2189,2352,2525,2700,2885,
%U A397444 3072,3269,3468,3677,3888,4109,4332,4565,4800,5045,5292,5549,5808,6077,6348,6629
%N A397444 Anion excess of a saturated rock-salt (NaCl) cube with n atoms along each edge: a(n) = 3*n^2 + 1 - (-1)^n.
%C A397444 a(n) = N_B - N_A, the excess of Cl anions over Na cations in a saturated rock-salt (NaCl) nanocube. The nanocube is an n X n X n block of atomic sites on the NaCl lattice (n sites per edge; n = 3 is a conventional NaCl unit cell), holding N_A = ceiling(n^3/2) Na cations. N_B counts the Cl anions once every surface Na is given its full 6-fold octahedral coordination (the saturated-surface limit: no reconstruction, vacancies, or adsorbates); the particle is anion-rich and a(n) is a nonnegative surface term.
%H A397444 D. Grebenyuk, <a href="https://github.com/grebenyyk/np-stoichiometry/blob/main/axby-np-stoichiometry/scripts/structures.py">Companion code (structures.py, function nacl_excess)</a>.
%H A397444 J. Jasieniak and P. Mulvaney, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1021/ja066205a">From Cd-Rich to Se-Rich: the manipulation of CdSe nanocrystal surface stoichiometry</a>, J. Am. Chem. Soc. 129 (2007), 2841-2848.
%H A397444 T. P. Martin, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0370-1573(83)90024-8">Alkali halide clusters and microcrystals</a>, Phys. Rep. 95 (1983), 167-199.
%H A397444 <a href="/index/Rec#order_04">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (2,0,-2,1).
%F A397444 a(n) = 3*n^2 + 1 - (-1)^n = 3*n^2 + 2*(n mod 2).
%F A397444 a(n) = N_B(n) - N_A(n), with N_A(n) = ceiling(n^3/2) and N_B(n) = floor(n^3/2) + 3*n^2 + 3*(n mod 2).
%F A397444 G.f.: x*(5+2*x+5*x^2)/((1-x)^3*(1+x)).
%F A397444 a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-3) + a(n-4), n >= 4.
%F A397444 E.g.f.: 3*x*(1 + x)*cosh(x) + (2 + 3*x + 3*x^2)*sinh(x). - _Stefano Spezia_, Jun 29 2026
%e A397444 a(3) = 29: a 3 X 3 X 3 saturated rock-salt nanocube has N_A = 14 cations and N_B = 43 anions, so the anion excess is 43 - 14 = 29 = 3*9 + 2.
%t A397444 a[n_] := 3*n^2 + 1 - (-1)^n; Array[a, 48, 0] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 25 2026 *)
%Y A397444 Cf. A036486 (N_A, the cation count of the same nanocube), A036487, A003215, A045943, A139274 (last three: analogous excess for CsCl, zincblende, and rutile nanocubes).
%K A397444 nonn,easy,new
%O A397444 0,2
